  "pages": [
    {
      "page_number": 1,
      "raw_text": "Probably for the first time in the\nhistory of the American labor\nmovement, a national convention\nis being held, beginning on Tues\nday in ST. Louis, which was OPP\nposed by the national officials and\nstrenuously demanded by the rank\nand file. Thirty thousand electrical\nworkers are represented in the con-\nvention, and the indications are\nthat nearly all the national officials\nwill be ousted by the membership,\nwho have taken matters in their\nown hands.\n\n\nThe fight between the national\nofficers and the rank and file is\nover the question of interpretations\nof laws. The sum of $4,000 is\ntied up by injunction in the banks\nof Cleveland, where the revolt\nagainst the officers started."
    }
